ce:section.ce:para:
To determine the functional groups and the surface chemical coating components, the FT-IR spectrum is measured and shown in Fig. 1 (f). The broadband absorption at about 3280 cm−1 corresponds to the stretching vibrations of –OH and N–H, and the absorption peaks at 2976, 1648, 1456, and 1040 cm−1 belong to C–H, C=O, C=C/ C–N, and C–O–C stretching vibration respectively [26,28]. The XPS spectra of MP-CQDs are shown in Fig. 1 (g) (h) (i), 285.6, 532.2, and 399.8 eV belong to C 1s, O 1s, and N 1s orbitals, and their percentage compositions are 37.28%, 60.35%, and 1.84% respectively (survey graph is shown in 
                           Fig. S1
                        ). C 1s band is separated into three peaks: 288.4, 286.3, and 284.8 eV, which is attributed to C=O, C–O/C–N, and C–C/C=C respectively; two fitting bands of O 1s are 532.7 and 531.5 eV, which are assigned to C–O and C=O; the N 1s band can also be separated into Pyrrolic N (399.7 eV) and Graphite N (401.0 eV) respectively [26,29]. According to FT-IR and XPS analysis, there are N, O, and carbonization-related functional groups in MP-CQDs, and such a result fits the fact that Mopan persimmons are rich in saccharides and protein.

As shown in Fig. 2 (b), the PL spectra of MP-CQDs represent intense excitation-dependent property, which originates from different surface groups, they make different surface states and edge states appear between the highest occupied molecular orbital (HOMO) and the lowest unoccupied molecular orbital (LUMO) energy bands (
                           Fig. S3
                        ) [30].
